Below is a **complete, ordered build guide** for your combined project:

> **Route 53 + Custom Domain + CloudFront + S3 (Private Origin + OAC + ACM HTTPS)**

This is a production-style setup. Follow the order exactly; AWS is sensitive to sequence here.

---

# 🧱 TARGET ARCHITECTURE (what you are building)

```
User
  ↓
Route 53 (systemsbyhamza.com DNS)
  ↓
CloudFront (HTTPS + caching)
  ↓
S3 (PRIVATE bucket via OAC)
```

---

# 0. PREREQUISITES

You will need:

* AWS account
* Domain: `systemsbyhamza.com` (buy via Route 53 later in step 1)
* Region awareness:

  * S3: any region
  * CloudFront: global
  * ACM: MUST be us-east-1 (important)

---

# 1. BUY DOMAIN (Route 53)

Go to:
Amazon Route 53

### Steps:

1. Open Route 53 console
2. Go to **Registered domains**
3. Click **Register domain**
4. Enter:

   * `systemsbyhamza.com`
5. Complete purchase

### Wait for:

* Domain status → “Active” (can take 5–30 minutes)

---

# 2. CREATE HOSTED ZONE (DNS CONTROL PLANE)

In Route 53:

1. Go to **Hosted zones**
2. Click **Create hosted zone**
3. Domain: `systemsbyhamza.com`
4. Type: Public hosted zone

You will now see:

* NS records
* SOA record

### IMPORTANT:

Route 53 will auto-link domain → hosted zone (if purchased in same account)

---

# 3. CREATE S3 BUCKET (PRIVATE ORIGIN)

Go to:
Amazon S3

### Steps:

1. Create bucket:

   * Name: `systemsbyhamza-static-origin`
   * Region: any (e.g. us-east-1)

2. SETTINGS (critical):

   * ❌ Block all public access = ON
   * Enable default encryption = ON

3. Upload file:

**index.html**

```html id="kq3v0a"
<html>
  <body>

    <h1>SystemsByHamza CloudFront Demo</h1>
    <p>Private S3 origin | Delivered via CloudFront</p>

<br><br>

    <h2>Popular Linux Distributions</h2>

    <p>Ubuntu</p>
    <img src="/images/ubuntu.png" width="140">

<br><br>

    <p>Fedora</p>
    <img src="/images/fedora.png" width="140">

<br><br>

    <p>Arch Linux</p>
    <img src="/images/arch.png" width="140">

  </body>
</html>
```

---

# 4. CREATE ACM CERTIFICATE (HTTPS)

Go to:
AWS Certificate Manager

### IMPORTANT RULE:

CloudFront ONLY uses ACM certificates from:

> **us-east-1 (N. Virginia)**

---

### Steps:

1. Switch region → **us-east-1**

2. Open ACM → Request certificate

3. Domain names:

   * `systemsbyhamza.com`
   * `www.systemsbyhamza.com`

4. Validation method:

   * Choose **DNS validation**

5. ACM will give CNAME records

---

### Now go back to Route 53:

* Hosted Zone → Add the ACM validation CNAME records
* Wait for:

  * Status → **Issued**

---

# 5. CREATE CLOUDFRONT DISTRIBUTION

Go to:
Amazon CloudFront

### Steps:

## Origin

* Origin domain: select your S3 bucket
* DO NOT use S3 website endpoint

---

## Enable Origin Access Control (OAC)

1. Click “Create Origin Access Control”
2. Settings:

   * Signing behavior: **Sign requests**
   * Origin type: S3

CloudFront will later generate S3 policy.

---

## Default cache behavior

* Viewer protocol policy: **Redirect HTTP → HTTPS**
* Allowed methods: GET, HEAD
* Cache policy: CachingOptimized (default is fine)

---

## Settings section

### Add:

* Alternate domain name (CNAME):

  * `systemsbyhamza.com`

### SSL Certificate:

* Select ACM cert (from us-east-1)

---

## Default root object:

```
index.html
```

---

# 6. FIX S3 BUCKET POLICY (CRITICAL STEP)

After CloudFront is created:

Go to CloudFront → copy generated **bucket policy**

Then:

S3 → Bucket → Permissions → Bucket Policy:

Paste policy similar to:

* Allow `cloudfront.amazonaws.com`
* Restrict to your distribution ARN

This enforces:

> ONLY CloudFront can read S3 objects

---

# 7. CREATE ROUTE 53 DNS RECORDS

Go to:
Amazon Route 53

Inside Hosted Zone:

## Create A record:

### Record 1 (root domain)

* Name: `systemsbyhamza.com`
* Type: A
* Alias: YES
* Target: CloudFront distribution

(Cloudfront automatically created two records, A and AAAA for itself for systemsbyhamza.com)

---

### Record 2 (www optional)

* Name: `www.systemsbyhamza.com`
* Type: CNAME
* Target: systemsbyhamza.com

---

# 8. TEST EVERYTHING

## Test 1: DNS resolution

```bash
nslookup systemsbyhamza.com
```

Should resolve to CloudFront.

---

## Test 2: HTTPS

Open:

```
https://systemsbyhamza.com
```

Expected:

* lock icon (TLS working)
* page loads from S3 via CloudFront

---

## Test 3: S3 direct access

Try S3 object URL:

❌ Should FAIL (AccessDenied)

This confirms:

> private origin is enforced

---

## Test 4: CloudFront caching

Open DevTools → Network tab:

Look for:

* `x-cache: Hit from cloudfront`
* `x-cache: Miss from cloudfront`

---

# 9. VERIFY SECURITY MODEL

You should now have:

### Public:

* Route 53 DNS
* CloudFront HTTPS endpoint

### Private:

* S3 bucket (fully blocked)
* No direct object access

---

# 🧠 WHAT YOU JUST BUILT (resume interpretation)

You now have:

### Edge networking layer

* CloudFront CDN
* global caching

### DNS routing layer

* Route 53 hosted zone
* domain ownership + resolution

### Secure storage layer

* private S3 origin
* OAC-based access control

### Security layer

* TLS via ACM
* origin shielding
* no public bucket exposure

---

